>>16205618
Imagine magical shit on a percentage level. Low is a low-as-fuck level of magic, but it's still there, while high fantasy has an ass-load of magic.

So say in a low fantasy D&D setting, there's legends of a wizard, but no one knows where the fuck he is and aren't even sure he exists at all, while in high fantasy they're just about fucking everywhere. This also extends to mythological creatures. So say something like Dragon's Dogma is high fantasy, while Monster Hunter is on a lower scale. Not at the near bottom, but certainly not reaching high levels.

There's two different definitions.
There's the D&D derived definitions which is what
>>16205783
Describes.

And then there's the literary definition, where low fantasy refers to settings that are supposed to be variants on our own world (like Harry Potter) and high fantasy refers to settings that are completely fabricated with their own histories and geography (like Game of Thrones.

The difference between these two definitions has caused much debate and confusion.
